  "theory": "The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is an algorithm that computes the Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) of a sequence extremely efficiently. While a direct calculation of an N-point DFT requires O(N^2) complex multiplications and additions, the Cooley-Tukey FFT algorithm reduces this computational complexity to O(N log2 N), enabling real-time digital signal processing. Decimation-in-Time (DIT) is one of the primary methods of structuring the FFT, where the input sequence x(n) is recursively decomposed (decimated) into its even-numbered and odd-numbered samples.\n\nFor an 8-point DIT FFT, the inputs must be arranged in bit-reversed order: x(0), x(4), x(2), x(6), x(1), x(5), x(3), and x(7). The computation is then performed across three distinct stages (log2 8 = 3 stages):\n1. Stage 1: Computes four independent 2-point DFTs (butterflies) using twiddle factors (W_8^0 = 1).\n2. Stage 2: Combines the Stage 1 outputs to compute two independent 4-point DFTs, utilizing twiddle factors W_8^0 and W_8^2.\n3. Stage 3: Combines the Stage 2 outputs to compute the final 8-point DFT, utilizing four twiddle factors: W_8^0, W_8^1, W_8^2, and W_8^3.\n\nEach butterfly node performs a basic mathematical operation: if inputs are A and B, the outputs are A + B * W and A - B * W, where W represents the complex exponential twiddle factor W_N^k = e^(-j * 2 * pi * k / N).",

  "keyPoints": [
    "Reduces DFT complexity from O(N^2) to O(N log2 N) using divide-and-conquer principles.",
    "Decimation-in-Time (DIT) splits the input sequence x(n) into even and odd index subsets.",
    "Input sequence must be sorted in bit-reversed order (e.g., index 001 -> 100 which is 1 -> 4).",
    "Requires log2 N stages (3 stages for an 8-point FFT) to complete the full calculation.",
    "Each butterfly computation calculates sums and differences weighted by twiddle factors (W_N^k).",
    "The outputs X(k) are obtained in natural, sequential order (X(0) through X(7))."
  ],

  "examTip": "Bit-reversal table for N=8: 0(000)->0(000); 1(001)->4(100); 2(010)->2(010); 3(011)->6(110); 4(100)->1(001); 5(101)->5(101); 6(110)->3(011); 7(111)->7(111). Remember that twiddle factors are always multiplied in the bottom legs of the butterflies before summing/subtracting.",

